handist.collections

Class ChunkedList<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • handist.collections.ChunkedList<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The type of the elements handled by the Chunks the ChunkedList contains, and by extension, the type of elements handled by the ChunkedList
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Iterable<T>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DistCol

    public class ChunkedList<T>
extends Object
implements Iterable<T>, Serializable
    Large collection containing multiple Chunks. This overcomes the storing limitation of individual Chunks. A ChunkedList can hold multiple Chunks, adjacent or not. However, it cannot contain Chunks whose bounds overlap. This is necessary to avoid having potentially multiple values associated with a single (long) index.
    See Also:
    Serialized Form

      • add_unchecked

        protected void add_unchecked(RangedList<T> c)
        Places the given ranged list without performing any checks.

        This is useful, particularly when splitting chunks as cannot afford a moment between which the original chunk is removed from the collection and the newer chunks are placed into the collection. As the newer chunks need to be placed first, for a brief instant, the ChunkedList will contain multiple ranges which overlap.

        Parameters:
        c - the chunk to place in the collection

      • asyncForEach

        public <U> Future<ChunkedList<T>> asyncForEach(ExecutorService pool,
                                               int nthreads,
                                               BiConsumer<? super T,Consumer<? super U>> action,
                                               ParallelReceiver<? super U> toStore)
        Performs the provided action on every element in the collection asynchronously using the provided executor service and the specified degree of parallelism. This method returns a FutureN.ReturnGivenResult which will wait on every asynchronous task spawned to complete before returning this instance. The provided action may initialize or extract a type U from the data contained in individual elements and give this type U to its second parameter (a Consumer of U) which will in turn place these instances in toStore. Note that if you do not need to extract any information from the elements in this collection, you should use method asyncForEach(ExecutorService, int, Consumer) instead.
        Type Parameters:
        U - the type of the information to extract from the instances
        Parameters:
        pool - executor service in charge or performing the operation
        nthreads - the degree of parallelism for this action, corresponds to the number of pieces in which this instance contents will be split to be handled by parallel threads
        action - to action to perform on each individual element contained in this instance, which may include placing a newly created instance of type U into the Consumer (second parameter of the lambda expression).
        toStore - instance which supplies the Consumer used the lambda expression to every parallel thread and will collect all the U instances given to those Consumers.
        Returns:
        a FutureN.ReturnGivenResult which waits on the completion of all asynchronous tasks before returning this instance. Programmers should also wait on the completion of this FutureN to make sure that no more U instances are placed into toStore.

      • asyncMap

        public <S> Future<ChunkedList<S>> asyncMap(ExecutorService pool,
                                           int nthreads,
                                           Function<? super T,? extends S> func)
        Creates a new ChunkedList defined on the same LongRanges as this instance by performing the mapping function on each element contained in this instance. This method applies the user-provided function in parallel using the threads in the provided ExecutorService with the set degree of parallelism by splitting the values contained in this instance into equal-size portions. These portions correspond to futures that complete when the portion has been dealt with. This method returns a FutureN.ReturnGivenResult which will return the newly created ChunkedList once all the individual futures have completed.
        Type Parameters:
        S - the type handled by the newly created map
        Parameters:
        pool - the executor service in charge of processing this ChunkedList in parallel
        nthreads - the degree of parallelism desired for this operation
        func - the mapping function from type T to type S from which the elements of the ChunkedList to create will be initialized
        Returns:
        a FutureN.ReturnGivenResult which will return the new ChunkedList once all parallel mapping operations have completed

      • contains

        public boolean contains(Object o)
        Checks if the provided object is contained within one of the Chunks this instance holds. More formally, returns true if at least one of the chunks in this instance contains at least one element 'e' such that (o==null ? e==null : o.equals(e)). Of course, there may be several such elements 'e' in this instance located in a single and/or multiple chunks.
        Parameters:
        o - object whose presence is to be checked
        Returns:
        true if the provided object is contained in at least one of the chunks contained in this instance

      • containsAll

        public boolean containsAll(Collection<?> c)
        Checks if all the elements provided in the collection are present in this instance.

        In its current implementation, it is equivalent to calling method contains(Object) with each element in the collection until either an element is not found in this collection (at which point the method returns false without checking the remaining objects in the collection) or all the elements in the provided collection are found in this instance (at which point this method returns true. If programmer can place the elements that are more likely to be absent from this instance at the beginning of the collection (in the order used by the Iterator, it may save considerable execution time.

        Parameters:
        c - elements whose presence in this instance is to be checked
        Returns:
        true if every instance in the provided collection is present in this collection

      • forEach

        public <U> void forEach(BiConsumer<? super T,Consumer<? super U>> action,
                        Collection<? super U> toStore)
        Performs the provided action on each element of this collection. As part of this operation, some information of type U can be created or extracted from elements and potentially stored into the provided collection using the Consumer of U (second argument of the lambda expression). These elements will be added using method Collection.add(Object).

        As a variant, you may also directly supply a Consumer<U> rather than a collection using method forEach(BiConsumer, Consumer)

        Type Parameters:
        U - the type of the information to extract
        Parameters:
        action - action to perform on each element of the collection
        toStore - the collection in which the information extracted will be stored
        See Also:
        forEach(BiConsumer, Consumer)

      • forEach

        public <U> void forEach(BiConsumer<? super T,Consumer<? super U>> action,
                        Consumer<? super U> receiver)
        Performs the provided action o neach element of this collection. As part of this operation, some information of type U can be created or extracted from elements and given to the Consumer<U> (second argument of the lambda expression). This Consumer available in the lambda expression is the one given as second parameter of this method.

        As an alternative, you can use method forEach(BiConsumer, Collection) to provide a Collection rather than a Consumer as the second argument of the method.

        Type Parameters:
        U - the type of the result extracted from the elements in this collection
        Parameters:
        action - the action to perform on each element of this collection
        receiver - the receiver which will accept the U instances extracted from the elements of this collection

      • forEach

        public <U> void forEach(BiConsumer<? super T,Consumer<? super U>> action,
                        ParallelReceiver<? super U> toStore)
        Performs the provided action sequentially on the instances contained by this ChunkedList, allowing for the by-product of the operation to be stored in the specified ParallelReceiver.

        This method is necessary as the manner in which instances are placed inside a ParallelReceiver differs from that of a normal collection. Although the features that handle parallel insertion of values are not leveraged in this sequential method, the preparations needed to insert instances into the ParallelReceiver remain necessary.

        Type Parameters:
        U - the type of the data produced from the instances contained in this collection and stored in the provided ParallelReceiver
        Parameters:
        action - the action performed on all the elements contained in this collection. U instances may be created and given to the Consumer<U> as part of this action
        toStore - the parallel receiver which will receive all the U instances which are created as part of the action applied on the elements of this collection
